                            <div class="course-description whitespace-pre-wrap">
This study focuses on German video artist Harun Farocki's late four-screen installation work "Parallel I-IV" (2012-2014), using it as a key text to delve into a profound philosophical exploration of the nature of computer-generated imagery (CGI). The paper argues that Farocki, by tracing the thirty-year technical evolution of video game images from abstract lines to realistic rendering, reveals that the core operating logic of digital images lies in "computation" and "simulation," rather than the traditional film theory-dependent "indexical representation" based on photography. This research not only challenges classical film ontology but also constructs a critical framework for examining how algorithms manipulate human perception patterns by quantifying natural laws and simulating the human sensory system while shaping a "realistic" experience.
                            </div>
