                                    <h3>1. Research Background and Core Object</h3>
                                    <p>This study is based on Farocki's creative methodology—especially "multi-screen installations" and "operative images"—treating the "Parallel" series as a key "media archaeology" practice. The work uses popular cultural products like video games as an entry point to philosophically reflect on the generative logic of digital images.</p>

                                    <h3>2. The Dual Logic of Digital Images: Computability and Simulability</h3>
                                    <p>The core argument of the paper is that the essence of digital images is an "ideal simulacrum." Its realism stems from:</p>
                                    <div class="concept-card">
                                        <h4>Computation</h4>
                                        <p>The quantification and abstraction of natural laws (such as physics, optics) by algorithms.</p>
                                    </div>
                                    <div class="concept-card">
                                        <h4>Simulation</h4>
                                        <p>The imitation and data reconstruction of the human sensory system (especially visual perception).</p>
                                    </div>
                                    <p>This logic means that digital images are generated, not recorded; their reference is internal mathematical models and sensory data models, rather than external reality.</p>

                                    <h3>3. Challenging Traditional "Representation" Concepts</h3>
                                    <p>Farocki's work juxtaposes the technological history of video game imagery with art historical imagery (such as Renaissance painting, modernist abstraction), thus proposing: the history of digital images is departing from the track of "representing reality," shifting towards constructing a self-consistent simulation system based on algorithms. This directly questions the "representation" ontology of traditional film theory, which is based on photography.</p>

                                    <h3>4. Extension of Technical Critique: Perceptual Manipulation and "Incomputability"</h3>
                                    <p>The study further points out that the deeper impact of this computation-simulation logic lies in the reshaping and manipulation of the human perceptual system. When algorithms can calculate and simulate sensory input, they acquire the potential power to influence or even define how we "see" and "interact." The paper ultimately directs its critique toward the question of the limits of this manipulation, that is, whether there exists a domain that algorithms cannot calculate or simulations cannot encompass—the philosophical proposition of "incomputability".</p>
